Former First Lady Barbara Bush, wife of 41st President George H. W. Bush, passed away at the age of 92. She was the only second woman in American history to serve as First Lady and raise a son who would become president. Barbara Bush was not only known for being a matriarch of a political family but also for her advocacy of literacy. She attended over 500 events related to literacy during her husband's time as Vice President. Her legacy extends beyond her role as a public figure, as she was remembered for her warmth and friendship. Barbara Bush was seen as a symbol of women's empowerment and valued accessibility as a First Lady. The Bush family and public officials paid tribute to her, emphasizing her impact as a First Lady and a mother. Her funeral will be attended by First Lady Melania Trump, and President Trump has ordered flags to be flown at half-staff until the day of her funeral.